16 programs under the "Quality Basic Education Act," by revising Code Section 20-2-308,
17 which is reserved, as follows:
18 "20-2-308.
19 (a) Beginning in the 2026-2027 school year, each local board of education shall be
20 authorized to provide instruction in hunting safety in grades six through 12, which
21 instruction may be incorporated into an existing course of study.
22 (b) No later than April 1, 2026, the State Board of Education shall adopt content standards
23 for such instruction in hunting safety.
24 (c) Each local board of education shall be authorized to establish a curriculum for
25 instruction in hunting safety, which curriculum shall be based on the hunter education
26 courses offered by the Department of Natural Resources.
27 (d) Instruction in hunting safety offered pursuant to this Code section shall be taught by
28 an individual who is certified as a hunter education instructor by the Department of Natural
29 Resources. Reserved."
30 SECTION 2.
31 Said chapter is further amended in Article 11, relating to public school property and facilities,
32 by adding a new part to read as follows:
33 "Part 4
34 20-2-590.
35 (a) The Department of Education is authorized to establish a pilot program, beginning in
36 the 2025-2026 school year, to provide for the development and study of outdoor learning
37 spaces on elementary and secondary school property. The purpose of the pilot program
38 shall be to determine whether and how to implement best practices and design standards
39 for outdoor learning spaces.
- 2 -

LC 61 0264S
40 (b) The Department of Education is authorized to select elementary or secondary schools
41 with sufficient existing or potential outdoor learning spaces for participation in the pilot
42 program as pilot schools. Private, nonprofit, and local school system funding may be
43 utilized by such pilot schools for community engagement, school grounds design support,
44 and capital construction costs. The local board of education for each pilot school shall
45 agree to implement a program to incorporate outdoor learning spaces into the existing
46 curriculum and to continue to provide such program for a period no shorter than three
47 years.
48 (c) The Department of Education shall provide for an evaluation regarding the success and
49 impact of the pilot program upon completion of the third year of the pilot program and
50 shall report the results of such evaluation to the House Committee on Education and the
51 Senate Education and Youth Committee."
52 SECTION 3.
53 Said chapter is further amended by revising Code Section 20-2-775, relating to automated
54 external defibrillators required in high schools, requirements, and funding, as follows:
55 "20-2-775.
56 (a) As used in this Code section, the term:
57 (1) 'Automated external defibrillator' means a defibrillator which:
58 (A) Is capable of cardiac rhythm analysis;
59 (B) Will charge and be capable of being activated to deliver a countershock after
60 electrically detecting the presence of certain cardiac dysrhythmias; and
61 (C) Is capable of continuously recording cardiac dysrhythmia at the scene with a
62 mechanism for transfer and storage or for printing for review subsequent to use.
63 (2) 'Emergency action plan' means the plan established pursuant to paragraph (5) of
64 subsection (c) of this Code section to provide for an emergency response to a person in
65 cardiac arrest.
- 3 -

